  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1560923784" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1560923784" />
    <a title="Rachel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5228293-rachel"><img alt="Rachel" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1560923784?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rachel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rachel" href="/user/show/5228293-rachel">Rachel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1560923784" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7469959326947798824">Yosuke Kirihara&apos;s dead body is found in an abandoned building, and Detective Sasagaki is unable to solve the case. Never one to give up, this novel traces the lives of the two main suspects over 18 years, with Sasagaki ever hovering in background. <br/><br/>To sum it up in one sentence, this is an infuriating and yet absorbing novel. One of the main flaws of this novel is that <i>it is extremely hard to keep track of the characters mentioned</i>. Higashino has the annoying tendency of introducing a seemingly end</span>
  <span id="freeText7469959326947798824" style="display:none">Yosuke Kirihara's dead body is found in an abandoned building, and Detective Sasagaki is unable to solve the case. Never one to give up, this novel traces the lives of the two main suspects over 18 years, with Sasagaki ever hovering in background. <br /><br />To sum it up in one sentence, this is an infuriating and yet absorbing novel. One of the main flaws of this novel is that <i>it is extremely hard to keep track of the characters mentioned</i>. Higashino has the annoying tendency of introducing a seemingly endless cast of characters that appears for three paragraphs, only to have them vanish by the next. Some do pop up again in the future, but most are disposable and recyclable. It got to the point where I had to make a list to keep up, and finished the book with a total tally of approximately 20 (it got to the point where I just could not be bothered to keep track anymore), out of which most were only mentioned once, and never again.<br /><br />To read and enjoy this novel, one must suspend one's common sense and logic. The reader must accept that <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[two elementary school kids aged approximately 10 years old are capable of carrying out a murder and two other suspicious deaths in quick succession without leaving any identifying evidence that would get them caught; that a few years later, the same two teenagers are separately or jointly capable of ensuring not one, but that <i>two</i> female classmates endure a sexual assault, cast suspicions on other classmates for the said assaults, run a gigolo ring, cover up a death, <i>and</i> successfully break the ATM encoding on ATM cards and withdrawn millions of yen, <b>all before they turn 30 and all without being caught</b>. Not only that, but as the years progress, the reader is expected to believe that these criminal geniuses also managed to infiltrate <i>two</i> technology companies, run a criminal ring, cause more people to die in suspicious circumstances (one of them a private detective, who was aware that he was being followed and that the person he was investigating was dangerous, and yet ignores all the warning signs that he was in danger and walks right into his own death), and <b>still get away with it without the bumbling police force being able to obtain any kind of clue or evidence as to the real perpetrator behind it.</b> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> With the way this novel plays out, either the police force in Japan are extremely incompetent, or the author expects his reader to be unquestioningly stupid. <br /><br />Despite the obvious weakness in the plot, I sped through this with ease, which is as per the case in most crime novels. Assuming you make it to the end of this 539 page paperback (Little, Brown; 2015 Edition), a most unsatisfying ending awaits you. Other crime novels exist, with better characters and tighter plots. Give this a try only if you are a masochist who enjoys being annoyed and unsatisfied.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7469959326947798824" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


