  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2599712311" />
    <a title="oshizu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/81879463-oshizu"><img alt="oshizu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578460220p2/81879463.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2599712311?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="oshizu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="oshizu" href="/user/show/81879463-oshizu">oshizu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/30531132-under-the-midnight-sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/81879463-oshizu?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/81879463-oshizu?shelf=z3-2019-read-in">z3-2019-read-in</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2599712311" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13378227967275002496">4.5 stars rounded up (compared with the Japanese edition which was a solid 5 stars).<br/>There were 3-4 short scenes in this translation which seemed conspicuously crasser, cruder than what I remember of the Japanese novel, which I read 4-5 years ago. <br/>I can&apos;t tell whether to attribute the difference to my faulty memory or to the English translation--that is, the artistic choices of the translation combined with the inherently more explicit nature of the English language. Most of the dialogue employed</span>
  <span id="freeText13378227967275002496" style="display:none">4.5 stars rounded up (compared with the Japanese edition which was a solid 5 stars).<br />There were 3-4 short scenes in this translation which seemed conspicuously crasser, cruder than what I remember of the Japanese novel, which I read 4-5 years ago. <br />I can't tell whether to attribute the difference to my faulty memory or to the English translation--that is, the artistic choices of the translation combined with the inherently more explicit nature of the English language. Most of the dialogue employed the Kansai dialect which, sadly, vanished in translation.<br />Still, a dark, twisted, perplexing, entertaining mystery.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13378227967275002496" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


